  <p data-reveal>There's a scene that plays out often in my practice: someone arrives frustrated with themselves over a behavior they can't seem to stop — procrastinating, overeating, exploding in anger, shutting down right when they need connection most. "I know I shouldn't do it," they say, "but something in me keeps doing it anyway."</p>
  <p data-reveal>That "something in me" is, to me, one of the most honest starting points in therapy. Because it already contains an important intuition: it's not all of you, in your totality, acting that way. It's a part.</p>

  <h2 data-reveal>The inner world has inhabitants</h2>
  <p data-reveal>The Internal Family Systems model was developed by therapist Richard Schwartz out of decades of clinical work. What he found, again and again, was that the psyche doesn't operate as a single monolithic unit but as a system of parts, each with its own history, its own logic, its own emotions and beliefs. And that this inner system resembles, in many ways, a family.</p>
  <p data-reveal>Schwartz identified three broad categories. <strong>Exiles</strong> are the parts that carry the oldest wounds — shame, fear of abandonment, the pain we learned not to show. They're vulnerable, which is why the system keeps them hidden. <strong>Managers</strong> are the parts that try to maintain control: the perfectionist, the one constantly tracking what others think, the one who plans and anticipates so nothing goes wrong. And <strong>firefighters</strong> are the emergency parts — the ones that step in when the exiles' pain threatens to overwhelm: the impulse to escape, to distract, to numb out with whatever's available.</p>
  <p data-reveal>None of these parts is the problem. All of them have a protective function, even if that function was designed for a past situation that no longer exists. The inner critic that won't stop pointing out your mistakes isn't your enemy — it's a part that learned that pushing you harder protected you from rejection. When you can see it that way, something shifts. The relationship with that voice stops being a war and becomes a possible dialogue.</p>
  <p data-reveal>Pat Ogden, a pioneer in somatic therapy, has pointed out something that resonates deeply with this model: parts don't only live in the mind — they also live in the body. The tension in the shoulders, the tightness in the chest before speaking in public, the knot in the stomach when someone disappoints you — all of that is information from the parts, expressing itself through physiology. That's why in my work IFS integrates naturally with <a href="/en/blog/body-based-therapy/" class="link-underline">body-based therapy</a> and with <a href="/en/blog/somatic-experiencing/" class="link-underline">Somatic Experiencing</a>: to listen not only to what the parts say, but to what they hold in the body.</p>

  <h2 data-reveal>The Self: what is already whole in you</h2>
  <p data-reveal>One of IFS's most radical premises is this: at the core of every person there is a Self — a presence that isn't damaged, that can observe with curiosity, calm, and without judgment. No matter how much pain you've carried, how many layers of protection have built up: that Self is still there. Therapy doesn't install anything new in you. It helps that core reclaim its place of leadership within the system.</p>
  <p data-reveal>Brené Brown has explored with great honesty how shame leads us to hide parts of ourselves — to build an acceptable version of ourselves and bury what doesn't seem to fit. IFS proposes exactly the opposite: that instead of hiding those parts, we invite them to be seen. That the Self — that curious, compassionate presence — be the one who approaches them, not to eliminate them, but to understand them.</p>
  <p data-reveal>In session, this translates into something that can initially seem strange: "speaking to" a part. Not in the sense of a theatrical dramatization, but of directing attention toward what's alive inside — a sensation, an emotion, a voice — and simply asking it what it needs. What often happens is surprising: the most rigid, the most defensive parts, the ones that have taken the most work, often carry very old stories waiting to be heard.</p>

  <h2 data-reveal>How IFS works in practice</h2>
  <p data-reveal>In my practice, IFS rarely shows up as an isolated protocol. I integrate it with other approaches depending on what the moment of the process calls for. Sometimes the entry point is a recurring belief — "I'm not enough," "if I show vulnerability I'll get hurt" — and from there we explore which part holds that belief and what it's protecting. Other times the entry point is somatic: a sensation that arises in session and that, when attended to, reveals a part that's been waiting for space.</p>
  <p data-reveal>It also connects fluidly with <a href="/en/blog/tapping-eft/" class="link-underline">Tapping / EFT</a> and with <a href="/en/blog/polyvagal-theory/" class="link-underline">Polyvagal Theory</a>, because the state of the nervous system directly influences which parts have access to the foreground and which stay blocked. When the nervous system is in threat mode, managers and firefighters take control. When there's enough physiological safety, the Self can show up.</p>
  <p data-reveal>What this model has taught me most — both in my own path and in the work with the people I accompany — is that transformation doesn't happen through elimination but through integration. It's not about getting rid of the critic, the anxious one, the one who flees. It's about those parts no longer having to carry the weight alone. About them being able to lay down roles they took on out of necessity and discover that there's something in you — that Self — that can take the reins with more wisdom and more love than they were ever able to offer.</p>
  <p data-reveal>That, in my experience, is what makes IFS a quiet revolution: it doesn't ask you to fix yourself. It invites you to know yourself.</p>
